      "solution": "# Easy or Medium difficulty.\n# Not original, I got this in a class before, but I can't find the problem.\n\nn = int(input())\ngrid = []\nfor _ in range(n):\n    grid.append(list(input()))\n\n# Count the number of corners instead\ncorners = 0\nfor i in range(n-1):\n    for j in range(n-1):\n        # Look at every 2x2 subgrid. If there are 1 or 3 black squares, there is a corner.\n        count = 0\n        for x, y in [(i,j), (i,j+1), (i+1,j), (i+1,j+1)]:\n            if grid[x][y] == '#':\n                count += 1\n                \n        if count == 1 or count == 3:\n            corners += 1\n\nprint(corners)\n\n# Another solution: Walk around the outside of the region and count the number of turns\n# Another solution: Double all inputs and count the number of \"#\" with two neighboring \"#\" in an L shape",
